00:25:02.878 --> 00:25:04.340
AUDIENCE: I have
two questions.

00:25:04.340 --> 00:25:09.352
One, your early anecdote about
your first angel investor, you

00:25:09.352 --> 00:25:13.810
said she told you she wanted you
to start a thrift shop for

00:25:13.810 --> 00:25:15.310
people like her?

00:25:15.310 --> 00:25:17.310
Did you ever find out exactly
what she meant?

00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:18.470
MATTHEW BERNARDO: She
meant that it was an

00:25:18.470 --> 00:25:19.420
upscale thrift store.

00:25:19.420 --> 00:25:23.920
That the idea was that she
actually had the model.

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:27.510
That the model of the thrift
store is that we actually go

00:25:27.510 --> 00:25:31.030
in and we go into very expensive
neighborhoods,

00:25:31.030 --> 00:25:33.460
because we get donations
from that neighborhood.

00:25:33.460 --> 00:25:38.510
And we then sell it to the same
people that are in that

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:39.000
neighborhood.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.870
So everything in retail
is about the product.

00:25:42.870 --> 00:25:46.340
So if we start out with a good
product and actually have the

00:25:46.340 --> 00:25:49.180
donations that are high-end,
you're going to be able to

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:51.710
have a lot easier time
than selling it.

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:53.390
So that's what she meant.

00:25:53.390 --> 00:25:54.940
She actually was right on.

00:25:54.940 --> 00:25:57.530
AUDIENCE: You didn't show those
pictures of the upscale

00:25:57.530 --> 00:25:58.237
thrift store.

00:25:58.237 --> 00:26:00.190
Those didn't come later
in your presentation.

00:26:00.190 --> 00:26:02.570
Was the very first thrift store,
did it have that same

00:26:02.570 --> 00:26:03.015
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:26:03.015 --> 00:26:04.350
Was it in an upscale
neighborhood?

00:26:04.350 --> 00:26:08.790
MATTHEW BERNARDO: Yeah, it was
on 18th Street and 7th Avenue.

00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:13.430
And then that lasted about six
months, and then we moved into

00:26:13.430 --> 00:26:16.800
17th Street, which is
our flagship store.

00:26:16.800 --> 00:26:19.270
And it's on 17th between
Sixth and Seventh.

00:26:19.270 --> 00:26:23.470
And the idea was that we had a
couple things going for us.

00:26:23.470 --> 00:26:26.970
One is that we were able to
beautifully merchandise it.

00:26:26.970 --> 00:26:28.940
So we believed in merchandising
products.

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:33.300
So our product were always had
these elaborate displays and

00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:35.110
sort of a quirkiness.

00:26:35.110 --> 00:26:37.580
Each of our stores is sort of a
mirror to the neighborhood.

00:26:37.580 --> 00:26:40.970
So our Upper East Side store
and Chelsea are going to be

00:26:40.970 --> 00:26:42.410
merchandised differently.

00:26:42.410 --> 00:26:43.540
So we had that.

00:26:43.540 --> 00:26:46.580
And remember, at the time, there
were many people that

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:48.300
were dying of HIV and AIDS.

00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:50.940
And we might not have been
getting the currency of their

00:26:50.940 --> 00:26:55.440
cash, but we were certainly
getting their estates and all

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:58.890
of the furniture and clothing
that they were bequeathing us.

00:26:58.890 --> 00:27:03.170
So that really was able to
sort of seed a very good

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:04.410
product base for us.

00:27:04.410 --> 00:27:08.850
And then it sort of caught fire,
and we were able to go,

00:27:08.850 --> 00:27:12.520
we ended up going online through
our auctions, and

00:27:12.520 --> 00:27:14.356
growing from there.

00:27:14.356 --> 00:27:17.132
AUDIENCE: I have a second
question, if that's OK.

00:27:17.132 --> 00:27:20.356
When you were talking about the
bookstore, you said it was

00:27:20.356 --> 00:27:22.958
unprofitable for the first few
years, and then you took off

00:27:22.958 --> 00:27:24.750
when you started selling
stuff online.

00:27:24.750 --> 00:27:26.958
So my question is, at that
point, from a business point

00:27:26.958 --> 00:27:28.985
of view, how do you justify
the bookstore's continued

00:27:28.985 --> 00:27:31.940
existence, once you find out
that at least at that point,

00:27:31.940 --> 00:27:34.470
the real money's in
online sales?

00:27:34.470 --> 00:27:37.670
MATTHEW BERNARDO: Well, because
of the bookstore, we

00:27:37.670 --> 00:27:40.990
were doing the online sales in
the basement, so it was part

00:27:40.990 --> 00:27:41.870
of the whole rent.

00:27:41.870 --> 00:27:44.370
The bookstore was producing
revenue.

00:27:44.370 --> 00:27:46.170
It's just it wasn't
necessarily--

00:27:46.170 --> 00:27:49.910
it was right around break-even
or losing money.

00:27:49.910 --> 00:27:52.010
And the bookstore brought
a lot of extra

00:27:52.010 --> 00:27:55.650
things into the bookstore.

00:27:55.650 --> 00:27:57.970
Like we had authors
that we'd get.

00:27:57.970 --> 00:28:00.270
It would garner a lot
of media attention.

00:28:00.270 --> 00:28:01.580
We had concerts.

00:28:01.580 --> 00:28:05.620
We have John Mellencamp, John
Cougar Mellencamp that played

00:28:05.620 --> 00:28:09.610
there, and Bjork DJed there.

00:28:09.610 --> 00:28:12.950
So there's a lot of things that
we could rationalize that

00:28:12.950 --> 00:28:17.870
we were getting the awareness
out through it.

00:28:17.870 --> 00:28:22.170
And we were just sort of not
making it as a great business

00:28:22.170 --> 00:28:22.830
proposition.

00:28:22.830 --> 00:28:25.820
Certainly, the time and energy
we were sinking into it wasn't

00:28:25.820 --> 00:28:27.620
paying off in the first
couple years.

00:28:27.620 --> 00:28:29.155
But we believed in it.

00:28:29.155 --> 00:28:34.790
We believed as part of the
social enterprise, that there

00:28:34.790 --> 00:28:38.320
was a way to make money, and
we would try a lot of

00:28:38.320 --> 00:28:38.810
different things.

00:28:38.810 --> 00:28:42.580
Now we have a cafe that's
growing, and we have the

00:28:42.580 --> 00:28:44.610
online that's growing,
and we have the

00:28:44.610 --> 00:28:45.670
events that are growing.

00:28:45.670 --> 00:28:47.460
So it's sort of like,
sometimes you have

00:28:47.460 --> 00:28:48.390
to figure it out.

00:28:48.390 --> 00:28:52.020
And sometimes just dumping it
costs more money there anyway.

00:28:52.020 --> 00:28:59.195
Because you have rents and
leases and so forth.

00:28:59.195 --> 00:29:01.640
AUDIENCE: So you kind of
discussed how the financial

00:29:01.640 --> 00:29:06.041
crisis in 2008 kind of, in
a way, I wouldn't say

00:29:06.041 --> 00:29:09.464
vindicated, but supported the
social enterprise model, which

00:29:09.464 --> 00:29:10.442
is [INAUDIBLE].

00:29:10.442 --> 00:29:15.150
Like in large part also saving
financially while maintaining

00:29:15.150 --> 00:29:16.940
your mission and goal.

00:29:16.940 --> 00:29:19.850
Do you think that that message
still resonates today?

00:29:19.850 --> 00:29:24.040
Or do you think because of the
recovery, NGOs are kind of

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:27.880
going back to donor focus
and development?

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:31.120
MATTHEW BERNARDO: Well, I think
there's two things.

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:36.160
One is that it's not completely
proven to the

00:29:36.160 --> 00:29:38.730
letter of the theory.

00:29:38.730 --> 00:29:42.430
But the theory is that
secondhand stores can be a

00:29:42.430 --> 00:29:44.650
little bit counter-cyclical
with the recession.

00:29:44.650 --> 00:29:48.960
So as people are sort of
looking for options to

00:29:48.960 --> 00:29:52.600
exercise their shopping muscle,
they're looking at

00:29:52.600 --> 00:29:58.050
other places that are
a better value.

00:29:58.050 --> 00:30:08.320
So with it, for example, 15% of
the people decided to shop

00:30:08.320 --> 00:30:10.190
secondhand stores for
the first time.

00:30:10.190 --> 00:30:12.020
So people started being
introduced to

00:30:12.020 --> 00:30:13.730
this in some ways.

00:30:13.730 --> 00:30:18.880
And so we do do slightly better
than regular mainline

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:20.770
retail on that.

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:23.330
The second thing, as far as
traditional fundraising, we

00:30:23.330 --> 00:30:26.530
really didn't have a traditional
development

00:30:26.530 --> 00:30:29.770
department until like 2004.

00:30:29.770 --> 00:30:34.260
And what we learned is very much
similar to how we merged

00:30:34.260 --> 00:30:38.950
the bookstore and the catering
to make it work.

00:30:38.950 --> 00:30:42.600
The businesses are really the
front door to our development

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:43.020
department.

00:30:43.020 --> 00:30:48.350
Now we are doing traditional
development at a better clip.

00:30:48.350 --> 00:30:50.240
We're getting individual
donors.

00:30:50.240 --> 00:30:53.390
We started a membership program
that actually is in

00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:54.780
all the stores.

00:30:54.780 --> 00:30:57.040
So that was the first way that
people were actually giving

00:30:57.040 --> 00:31:00.960
cash instead of just
giving product.

00:31:00.960 --> 00:31:05.530
Our events brings a really
well-heeled community into the

00:31:05.530 --> 00:31:08.610
events, and we start
working them and

00:31:08.610 --> 00:31:10.430
bringing them out to lunches.

00:31:10.430 --> 00:31:16.760
And we're starting to get some
multiple-figure donations, in

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:18.390
terms of the estates.

00:31:18.390 --> 00:31:20.380
Last year, we were able
to get an anonymous

00:31:20.380 --> 00:31:22.346
donation for $750,000.

00:31:22.346 --> 00:31:26.410
That was the first time we've
ever had something that large.

00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:30.430
So really, the businesses were
our front door to development.

00:31:30.430 --> 00:31:32.960
So we're taking advantage
of it wherever

00:31:32.960 --> 00:31:33.950
they're coming in from.

00:31:33.950 --> 00:31:36.100
So we're getting much more
sophisticated about our

00:31:36.100 --> 00:31:39.630
development now, so.

00:31:39.630 --> 00:31:42.582
AUDIENCE: You had a graph
that showed [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:48.570
Why do you think that is?

00:31:48.570 --> 00:31:55.590
MATTHEW BERNARDO: Well, it was
that you were dying faster,

00:31:55.590 --> 00:32:00.610
and that the circumstances of
being really vulnerable

00:32:00.610 --> 00:32:03.080
allowed you to have
entree into this

00:32:03.080 --> 00:32:04.340
opportunistic disease.

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:09.060
So again, it goes back to sort
of, if you are not housed,

00:32:09.060 --> 00:32:10.950
then you are living
a chaotic life.

00:32:10.950 --> 00:32:14.240
When you're living a chaotic
life, you're more likely to

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:17.220
get into situations that
you're finding

00:32:17.220 --> 00:32:19.530
opportunistic disease.

00:32:19.530 --> 00:32:22.060
The story of HIV and
AIDS cannot be

00:32:22.060 --> 00:32:23.340
told without poverty.

00:32:23.340 --> 00:32:25.230
It cannot be told
without racism.

00:32:25.230 --> 00:32:28.000
And it cannot be told
without homophobia.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:32.540
If you look at where it sort of
spread from, it started in

00:32:32.540 --> 00:32:40.970
the gay community, and now it's
mostly in the people of

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:44.760
color and that's where it's
sort of transferred to.

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:47.820
So you start seeing
a lot of these

00:32:47.820 --> 00:32:51.906
underpinnings with the disease.

00:32:51.906 --> 00:32:54.351
AUDIENCE: How long ago did
Housing Works implement the

00:32:54.351 --> 00:32:56.310
auctions that they have
[INAUDIBLE] storefronts?

00:32:56.310 --> 00:32:58.670
MATTHEW BERNARDO: We always
had auctions.

00:32:58.670 --> 00:33:01.050
We did it as paper auctions.

00:33:01.050 --> 00:33:04.210
So there was a time when people
would, we would always

00:33:04.210 --> 00:33:07.260
do these windows, and people
would go in and they write

00:33:07.260 --> 00:33:10.050
down the auction, and there was
a time that it would end,

00:33:10.050 --> 00:33:15.110
and everyone would crowd around
for the winning bid.

00:33:15.110 --> 00:33:18.200
And literally, people were at
the register, putting their

00:33:18.200 --> 00:33:20.150
last bid, and then that's
how it was.

00:33:20.150 --> 00:33:24.090
So we then decided, well, that's
really only good for

00:33:24.090 --> 00:33:26.050
individual stores,
and we're only

00:33:26.050 --> 00:33:27.480
drawing from that community.

00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:30.220
So we decided to put
them online, and

00:33:30.220 --> 00:33:32.330
we did online auctions.

00:33:32.330 --> 00:33:36.720
And we have
shophousingworks.com, which

00:33:36.720 --> 00:33:41.540
does about $1 and 1/2 million
a year through our auctions.

00:33:41.540 --> 00:33:43.030
And it opened up the base.

00:33:43.030 --> 00:33:46.650
Now we have people all over the
country that actually buy

00:33:46.650 --> 00:33:49.250
from it, and we ship
to most places.

00:33:49.250 --> 00:33:52.230
We have people in other
countries that

00:33:52.230 --> 00:33:53.910
are buying from us.

00:33:53.910 --> 00:33:59.500
And also, the auctions were a
great way to sort of be a

00:33:59.500 --> 00:34:01.410
check on that we're getting
the right price.

00:34:01.410 --> 00:34:03.180
Because it really is
an open market.

00:34:03.180 --> 00:34:05.190
So we had an example--

00:34:05.190 --> 00:34:10.340
once we had this piece of art
that we were going to price.

00:34:10.340 --> 00:34:11.430
We priced it at $25.

00:34:11.430 --> 00:34:12.929
We threw it in the auction.

00:34:12.929 --> 00:34:14.989
We figured it'll go
where it goes.

00:34:14.989 --> 00:34:18.570
$17,000 later, we realized that
this was a piece of art

00:34:18.570 --> 00:34:19.530
that was worth it.

00:34:19.530 --> 00:34:22.110
I'm sure we've had something
slip through our fingers, and

00:34:22.110 --> 00:34:23.409
that's part of thrifting.

00:34:23.409 --> 00:34:24.739
That's part of the game.

00:34:24.739 --> 00:34:27.290
That's part of the hunt, that
people want to find these

00:34:27.290 --> 00:34:28.210
great things.

00:34:28.210 --> 00:34:34.179
But the online auctions have
really helped us put things

00:34:34.179 --> 00:34:40.050
that we're not sure about on a
bigger market that we can get

00:34:40.050 --> 00:34:41.489
the most for.

00:34:41.489 --> 00:34:42.763
AUDIENCE: That's a great
way of putting it.

00:34:42.763 --> 00:34:44.357
Like things that you're
not quite sure about.

00:34:44.357 --> 00:34:44.835
MATTHEW BERNARDO: Yeah.

00:34:44.835 --> 00:34:46.906
AUDIENCE: Because yeah, you
walk by, and you get that

00:34:46.906 --> 00:34:48.979
impression that there have got
to be some things that are

00:34:48.979 --> 00:34:50.035
true [INAUDIBLE], really.

00:34:50.035 --> 00:34:52.720
Oh, maybe I could have found
it in Housing Works in the

00:34:52.720 --> 00:34:53.870
not-auction area.

00:34:53.870 --> 00:34:55.060
I've had a few wins there.

00:34:55.060 --> 00:34:55.929
MATTHEW BERNARDO: Yeah, yeah.

00:34:55.929 --> 00:34:56.949
That's good, that's good.

00:34:56.949 --> 00:34:59.930
But generally, the rule is
anything signed, we try to put

00:34:59.930 --> 00:35:06.450
in window so we can do that.

00:35:06.450 --> 00:35:07.530
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:35:07.530 --> 00:35:07.910
MATTHEW BERNARDO: All right.

00:35:07.910 --> 00:35:09.260
Well, thank you very
much for your time.

00:35:09.260 --> 00:35:10.160
I appreciate it.

00:35:10.160 --> 00:35:12.527
[APPLAUSE]

